					#reddiv
					p  Cryo-electron tomography is an imaging technique used to produce high-resolution, 3D views of biological samples, think of it as a CT scan for cells. In contrast to other electron tomography techniques, samples are immobilized in non-crystalline ("vitreous") ice and imaged under cryogenic conditions, allowing them to be imaged without dehydration or chemical fixation, which could otherwise disrupt or distort biological structures. 


